<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911231-0018</DOCNO><DOCID>911231-0018.</DOCID><HL>   Glen Ivy Financial   Set to Pay $250,000   To Settle Charges</HL><DATE>12/31/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   RIVERSIDE, Calif. -- California law enforcement officialssaid Glen Ivy Financial Group and related entities agreed topay penalties and costs totaling $250,000 as part of asettlement of civil allegations of unfair competition anddeceptive representations by the company.   Glen Ivy, one of the nation's largest developers oftime-share resorts, didn't admit any violations of law. Thecompany, based in Corona, Calif., said it &quot;entered into thisagreement to ensure that the company has the confidence ofthe regulators, its lenders and customers.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   A spokesman for the California attorney general said acriminal investigation is being conducted, but he declined toelaborate.   The settlement of civil charges, approved Friday by astate court in Riverside, includes an undertaking by Glen Ivythat it won't sell rights to the same unit to more than onebuyer, that it won't alter documents and that it will notifypurchasers of a legal, three-day &quot;cooling off period,&quot; inwhich a purchase may be rescinded by the buyer. The companyalso agreed to appoint a &quot;compliance officer&quot; to monitor itstransactions.   As previously reported, the offices of Glen Ivy and GlenIvy Holdings Inc., a related company, were raided early thismonth by more than 100 California law enforcement agents whoshowed up with a search warrant and began a review, expectedto take months, of thousands of documents.   Glen Ivy has about 60,000 members in 24 resorts inCalifornia, Texas, Arizona, and five other Western states.</TEXT></DOC>